Pros:
Loki is Super sweet. And is a total goofball. He loves pets and snuggles. He loves playing with
bigger dogs, he thinks he’s a big dog. Can go all night (12+ hours) without peeing. So he can
hold his bladder. He can be left alone for hours without getting into anything, when he is alone
he mostly naps till you get back. He won’t get into trash or snacks lying around. He likes women
more than men. He's very energetic and loves to run around. He’s a very quiet dog. He is a
protector of his family. His favorite treats are bully sticks and bones, he’s a big chewer. He is
very trainable, and knows the commands sit, stay, down, leave it, wait, come, and high five. He
was trained as a service dog for anxiety and learned his service dog duties very well. He was
trained to help with my anxiety attacks and to snuggle me when I’m crying. He does very well
with a firm leader as long as the person isn’t “his” person. He’s great with other dogs his size or
bigger. Bigger dogs make him feel safe. He’s usually responsive to commands, listens well.
Very important that he not have one person to get attached to at his new home, he should be
part of a group of dogs with a group of people. He will be happier and less stressed this way.

Cons:
He Growls when he gets scared or threatened, hardly ever barks. He is Not great with small
dogs. 
Loki will appreciate an all adult home or if with kids 16 and older.

He doesn’t see all that well and doesn’t always recognize “friends.” He has a
high prey drive so if cats or small dogs or small animals run he will chase them.

animal.description: Jobie is one of those dogs that you just want to sit down and have a comforting heart to heart talk with and comfort him from his fears in life. He is a 3-4 year old, Shepherd mix boy who was found a few years ago just roaming free and scared of everyone. Somehow a man who saw him for months hanging around his business, caught him and took him home to foster and find a home. Soon it was apparent that Jobie needed a trained foster who could bring him to another level of confidence and ease with people. Jobie has come so far and he is not over all his fears but he can live more comfortably in this world, and we are so proud of him. He is housebroken, crate trained and playful when he trusts you and warms to your presence. He is still a work in progress but if he had a home where the people leashed him daily and took him for walks and did one on one things very consistently, then Jobie would move forward even more. He will bark when he is loose in the fenced yard...just a quirk. He will need experienced and patient owners who have worked with shy dogs before. Time, love and some confident work with him will produce more progressive results each day. We are looking for a quiet household with no young children, maybe teens but still a calm and quiet household. Another confident easy going dog would be a great companion and example for Jobie to have in his life. A big brother or sister who can show him that there is nothing to fear in life. He needs a calm household of people and a calm dog to be his mentor and big brother or sister, if you have these things to offer please contact us at ccrtennessee@gmail.com

They are loving indoor life and quickly adjusting to being housedogs.  They are excellent in their crates!  They are perfectly happy and quiet while foster Dad works from home.

He was never destructive…just a collector of things!  He is busy in the house but will happily settle down for a chew or a peanut butter kong.  

Wylie loves people.  He is very sweet and gentle.  He gets very excited to see other dogs on our walks and has been very friendly with the few he has met.  Wylie is also very good with our cats.  Initially he was excited to see the cats but he is very respectful and kind with them

animal.description:
Frosty is a 15-year-old Chihuahua dog. This boy was taken by his owners to a shelter to be put to sleep. We called to ask if we could see this little guy, When we first picked him up, we feared that he would indeed need to be put to sleep. He hurt whenever he was touched, tried to bite and could not go to the bathroom. He had a lump by his penis about the size of a golf ball.

Our vet said he had a strong heart and clear lungs, but desperately needed surgery. It was found he had an impeded testicle and it had turned cancerous. His teeth started falling out when he was examined. Dr. Spencer thought he could remove all the cancer tissues and the remainder of his teeth.

Frosty yelped in pain every time he was handled before his surgery but is now doing great after healing. He enjoys going out for some fun in the sun; he returns to the door and barks when he wants in. He needs a quiet home full of love to live out the final chapter of his life.

He weights 6 lb, is leash- and crate-trained. He is fully vetted, neutered, microchipped or can be with a voucher.

He can be seen at our adoption event or by appointment to approved applicants or at our adoption events. For more information, please visit http://FurrEverPetsRescue.org or call (9 a.m.-8 p.m.)/text Ione Fried, (903) 918-3213.

ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html

IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

Treats are his favorite and will

y treat is involved.

today at www.underhoundrailroad.org

animal.description:
~~~~~

Lauren is a 1 year old rat terrier mix. Was left on the side of the road. A nice Samaritan  posted her on the local Lost pups page and no one ever contacted her- She called us as she couldn't keep her and we went ahead and had all of her vetting done. She is all up to date and ready to go home! 

~~~~~

Due to Covid-19 concerns, we are not planning any public adoption events. If you are pre approved , we will call to set up an appointment to come and meet the dog and potentially take them home. It is by appointment only- 
Dogs will be brought into the outdoor kennel for you to meet and make your decision. MASKS WILL BE MANDATORY to maintain EVERYONE'S safety  NO EXCEPTIONS PLEASE !! Unless otherwise noted, the puppies and dogs listed will arrive on Saturday, December 5th, 2020 .
Please follow this link to fill out an application. It is step one in adopting a pup from our rescue.
http://littlerhodyrescue.com/adoption-application/ 

*Filling an application does not guarantee you as the adopter. All applicant's references will be called. PLEASE call your veterinarian and personal references and allow consent to speaking with us ! 
We cannot process your application otherwise. Failure will put your application in 'Limbo"  
We process applications as they arrive. The first approved applicant will be called and the pup taken off of Petfinder. We do not have the man/ woman power to all all other applicants to advise them. 
IF there s another dog that you are interested in as well, please list at the top of the application and we will enter your application for that pup if the first choice has been adopted. 

THANK YOU !!! You are giving a first rate dog a second chance....By adopting! 

***** SADLY , we need to put this in print: THIS IS A RESCUE DOG. We do NOT know their birthday / age.  (unless other wise noted)  
More often than not, OUR TEAM  has saved them from euthanasia in Southern shelters. 
We do not know any more than our Veterinarians offer to us. 
 We often have them in kennels, and utilize crate training.  House training status is often NOT KNOWN. 
Prior Health, estimated weight  (as an adult), breed (Including the parents' breed , size or mix)   and some health concerns are  NOT KNOWN unless our veterinarians discover it and offer the information to us.   Again, these are strays and turn ins from all over the country. They do NOT come with labels; nor guarantees. 

Characteristics and disposition can and will evolve with time.
YOU the adopter are responsible to train and keep up to date on vaccines and preventatives.  
YOU the adopter are responsible for taking care of this new member of your family. 
 *************

****
Our adoption fees are $ 600. This fee includes the transportation of the pet from one of the organizations that we work with in TX, LA or TN. Before joining us in RI all dogs are: spayed/neutered, microchipped, up to date on age-appropriate vaccines, and on de-wormers, flea/tick and heartworm prevention. In addition, all adults (6 months +) are heartworm tested and MUST be negative for both heartworm and microfilaria before transport. 

In addition to the above, all dogs must have a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection and be deemed healthy per USDA law in order to travel. Once they have been certified they are then transported via USDA transport services only, which is required by law. 
 We  sometimes don't understand how bad the situation is for these pups and dogs in southern states.  Many people in the south don't spay or neuter their pets as we do here. Subsequently, there are thousands of beautiful , worthy pups and dogs, kittens and cats  that are dumped, shot, abandoned, brought into shelters, neglected, abused and abandoned.  We step in , tend to their veterinary needs. As you can see above, we never fail to properly spay and neuter. Everything is done with the  caring , capable hands of our veterinarians to get them healthy and ready to place them for adoption. That's when we put the demand for family- friendly pets with the supply ..... 

Give a first rate dog a second chance!!!! ADOPT! 


Keep in mind that we also offer a two week return policy for the return of a healthy dog that includes a full refund. We want to make sure that the adoption is a perfect fit for both you and the dog.

If you would like more information about adopting please select "More About Little Rhody Rescue" where you will also find our online application if you'd like to proceed with the adoption process. Thank you!

My name is Jodie and I am a beautiful German Shepherd. Please don't let my beauty fool you though...I am truly a special needs dog. I will need LOTS and LOTS of patience. I need a dedicated owner who will understand my protective nature and keep me safe. I will need training, dedication and patience.
 
Adoption fee: $400
 
Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.

animal.description:
~~~~~
Momma Leela is the mother to the PEANUTS GANG Puppies ! 
 She was picked up off of the street in rural Louisiana...  running house to house frantically hoping for a meal.....HEAVILY pregnant to boot. 
 She was so so scared when she came in to the fosters home- She is so patient and tender with the foster family's children (  toddler and infant)  She is gentle, loving and sweet. Three days after arrival, she graced us with 7 more puppies to spay and neuter.  She has proven herself a tender , dedicated and attentive momma! 
 She is a Manchester terrier, cattle dog and basset mix. We do not know what the father is.  She weighs a whopping 25 pounds.  She had a HORRIBLE case of Mastitis... as the pups were weaning.  Several days of strong antibiotics and she was back in shape to be spayed! 
Now that she is spayed, Microchipped, vaccinated and de wormed she is ready for a soft spot on the sofa!  She is current on Flea tick meds and Heart worm prevention as well 
~~~~~

Due to Covid-19 concerns, we are not planning any public adoption events. If you are pre approved , we will call to set up an appointment to come and meet the dog and potentially take them home. It is by appointment only- 
Dogs will be brought into the outdoor kennel for you to meet and make your decision. MASKS WILL BE MANDATORY to maintain EVERYONE'S safety  NO EXCEPTIONS PLEASE !! Unless otherwise noted, the puppies and dogs listed will arrive on Saturday, December 5th, 2020 .
Please follow this link to fill out an application. It is step one in adopting a pup from our rescue.
http://littlerhodyrescue.com/adoption-application/ 

*Filling an application does not guarantee you as the adopter. All applicant's references will be called. PLEASE call your veterinarian and personal references and allow consent to speaking with us ! 
We cannot process your application otherwise. Failure will put your application in 'Limbo"  
We process applications as they arrive. The first approved applicant will be called and the pup taken off of Petfinder. We do not have the man/ woman power to all all other applicants to advise them. 
IF there s another dog that you are interested in as well, please list at the top of the application and we will enter your application for that pup if the first choice has been adopted. 

THANK YOU !!! You are giving a first rate dog a second chance....By adopting! 

***** SADLY , we need to put this in print: THIS IS A RESCUE DOG. We do NOT know their birthday / age.  (unless other wise noted)  
More often than not, OUR TEAM  has saved them from euthanasia in Southern shelters. 
We do not know any more than our Veterinarians offer to us. 
 We often have them in kennels, and utilize crate training.  House training status is often NOT KNOWN. 
Prior Health, estimated weight  (as an adult), breed (Including the parents' breed , size or mix)   and some health concerns are  NOT KNOWN unless our veterinarians discover it and offer the information to us.   Again, these are strays and turn ins from all over the country. They do NOT come with labels; nor guarantees. 

Characteristics and disposition can and will evolve with time.
YOU the adopter are responsible to train and keep up to date on vaccines and preventatives.  
YOU the adopter are responsible for taking care of this new member of your family. 
 *************

****
Our adoption fees are $ 600. This fee includes the transportation of the pet from one of the organizations that we work with in TX, LA or TN. Before joining us in RI all dogs are: spayed/neutered, microchipped, up to date on age-appropriate vaccines, and on de-wormers, flea/tick and heartworm prevention. In addition, all adults (6 months +) are heartworm tested and MUST be negative for both heartworm and microfilaria before transport. 

In addition to the above, all dogs must have a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection and be deemed healthy per USDA law in order to travel. Once they have been certified they are then transported via USDA transport services only, which is required by law. 
 We  sometimes don't understand how bad the situation is for these pups and dogs in southern states.  Many people in the south don't spay or neuter their pets as we do here. Subsequently, there are thousands of beautiful , worthy pups and dogs, kittens and cats  that are dumped, shot, abandoned, brought into shelters, neglected, abused and abandoned.  We step in , tend to their veterinary needs. As you can see above, we never fail to properly spay and neuter. Everything is done with the  caring , capable hands of our veterinarians to get them healthy and ready to place them for adoption. That's when we put the demand for family- friendly pets with the supply ..... 

Give a first rate dog a second chance!!!! ADOPT! 


Keep in mind that we also offer a two week return policy for the return of a healthy dog that includes a full refund. We want to make sure that the adoption is a perfect fit for both you and the dog.

If you would like more information about adopting please select "More About Little Rhody Rescue" where you will also find our online application if you'd like to proceed with the adoption process. Thank you!

If you are interested in this pet, please fill out an online Pre-Adoption Inquiry on our Website:  ARNELLHUMANE.ORG  under the tab “Adopt" on our Home Page, The Inquiry will introduce yourself and let us know which animal you are interested in adopting. 
 You will be contacted by phone or reply email for an Adoption Appointment.   All visits and Adoptions are by Appointment Only.   Appointments will be made in the order the inquiries are made and meet the needs of the pet.   Thank you.

Sly is a 1 year old Yellow Lab mix. He is a handsome dog with Lab personality and size.   Sly is all about the adventure ahead.  He enjoys playing with toys, running around with them in his mouth is by far his favorite. Sly sits automatically for a treat or before you throw the ball.  He is very quick to learn. 
 Knows sit for a treat very well. He is a smart boy. 
  We have had Sly play with young 4 month old pups and a female Lab mix and he was great - running from, chasing, wrastlin', and having a good old time taking whatever they dished out. Sly is okay with some dogs but reactive to those that intimidate him.  Sly would do well as an only dog with an active family or with another dog of similar play style.  He is large and strong but seems to like the chasing games over the rough and tumble. animal.description:
Toby was part of an accidental litter (his Mom is Husky and Dad is Chesapeake Bay Retriever mix). He ended up being homed way too early away from his Mom where he lived most of his first months on a porch without much interaction of the family, any other dogs or met any new people. At only 5 months old he was surrendered to the shelter. He was too fearful there and went straight to a foster home where he is blossoming being around his calm and yet assertive foster Mom. Toby just needs some reassurance that the world is not such a scary place.


Video of Toby with his friend Olive:
https://youtu.be/-UTQWvt4QK4
Toby's rescue journey video:
https://youtu.be/arCu_Hy-FGw

It takes Toby a little extra time to warm up to new people. He is learning that new environments are really not that scary after all.

Toby is 9 months old and a big boy, currently weighs about 60 lbs. Once fully grown he should be around 75 lbs.

He is microchipped, neutered, up to date on all vaccines and on heartworm and flea/tick prevention.

Toby sleeps well on his dog bed at night next to his humans. He can be crated for short period of times. He loves going for car rides and outings. 

This sweet fella enjoys playing with his toys and chewing on his chew toys like antlers and nylabones. 

Toby would do best in a home without very young children due to being a big puppy and could knock them over. He is not cat-tested.
Toby has gotten along with the other dogs in the past at his foster home ranging from a small Chihuahua to a Border Collie mix. Toby can play a bit rough at times and can be domineering but just needs some correction.

This boy will benefit being with someone who is familiar with the Husky breed and who can exercise him by walking and hiking with him, and taking him running. He walks well on the leash and can get a bit excited when he sees another dog but can be easily redirected with a treat.

Toby is such a fun and happy fella who loves to cuddle and snuggle with his humans.

If you think you can provide Toby the loving home he deserves and you have the patience and time to work with him send us an email and request an application: NeedfulSoulsDogRescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
Currently in foster in Puyallup, Washington. Lobo was a drop-off out in the country. Heaven only knows why. He is a Lab mix (about 60#s) and very friendly and a bit rambunctious. Judging an energy level from 1-10 (1 is the old Hound Dog; 10 is the Jack Russell that is like the Energy Bunny)... he is about a 7-8. I believe with exercise and training, he will settle down... most of the time. He has not had any training but he's very happy. We think he is about 4 yrs old. He was very skinny but is doing fabulous. He is a higher energy dog and you would think he was 1 not about four! lol

 

Children: Lobo is great with children but because of his high energy level, I wouldn't have him around young children. They need to be at least 12 or older. He will be a good partner for hiking, swimming, bicycling ...(you, not him), etc.

 

Cats: He does chase cats. Must be in a cat-less house or at least keep them totally separate.

Heartworm Tested: He is HEART WORM NEG.

 

House Training: We believe he has been an outside dog most of his life. Along with the behavior training, potty training should be easy because he's never known he could do his business in the house. It's just a matter of bonding and communicating.

 

Adoptions include neuter/spay, vaccinations (DHPP, Bordetella, Rabies), microchip, transport with one of our professional dog transporters, and 6 mos of heartworm prevention..

 

If you have any questions, text me... 210-394-6060.

 

Lobo is available for pre-adoption. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out the on-line application. COPY and PASTE the application link .

http://shaynesrescue.com/adoption-application-pet-central-satx/

 

You can also go to our Facebook page...

https://www.facebook.com/Pet-Central-SATX-866684826744181/

and LIKE us to help us out.

 

GET IN LINE FIRST: If you are interested in this dog, please fill out the application (link listed above). The rescue will contact you once the application is received. Although we strive to answer everyone, due to the high volume of inquiries we receive, we cannot guarantee a response to all emails. Filling out the application is the ONLY way to ensure a response from the rescue. In addition, while you are emailing us, if others apply, you lose out adopting the dog you chose. We have hundreds of puppies/dogs available so there really is no need to apply anywhere else. Also, one application is good even if you are interested in several different dogs...one application no matter which one you choose. We try to make it as easy as possible for you but if you are applying or have applied anywhere else, we do need to know that, too.

 

SHANYE'S FOSTERS is a group of foster parents in the Olympia/Tumwater area. We foster dogs for rescues and assist them in adopting/rehoming of their pups/dogs by listing on this site. Many dogs posted here are available to pre adopt NOW directly from the rescue. The only ones in foster in the NW specifically state that. We have very few fosters so most need to be pre adopted. All adoption fees go towards rescuing more dogs in need. No one receives a salary. Shayne's Fosters is not responsible for any experience you have with any dog you might see posted on this site. They are the property of the sponsoring rescue who will supply all medical supporting records which is given with each dog when adopted.

 

Our adoption fees cover all medical costs to make sure the pups are appropriately vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and spayed/ neutered. It also covers the cost of transport from Texas and the necessary health certificate documentation. The fees also include a negative heartworm test for any dogs over 6 months. Some dogs have additional medical, such as FHO, ACL, hernias, dental, and a myriad of other vetting. We do full disclosure of medical care/situations. If the adoption fees seem high (which never cover the true cost of rescue), we recommend fostering for a good rescue. Fostering ensures you incur no vet bills and no boarding fees. We are always in need of good fosters. We are all volunteers who donate our time and resources to help save as many dogs/pups lives as we possibly can.

 

Thank you for choosing to adopt a rescue pup/dog. Over 1 billion dogs worldwide are put to sleep (PTS) annually... thousands daily. The dog pounds PTS entire litters, pregnant/nursing moms and wonderful dogs that can make someone a great companion. We firmly believe there is NO breed other than "rescue" for all species. Thank you for being part of the village it takes to save these precious lives.

animal.description:
This sweet bonded, mother and son pair came into rescue this summer.  They were both in need of basic vetting, and Atka's eyes were a hot mess, he needed entropean surgery.  Now that vetting has been completed and Atka's eyes have healed, they are ready to find their forever home.  We will not separate them, so please, if you are not interested in adopting them as a pair, do not ask us to split them up.

These two are a gorgeous pair of smaller husky, in the 45lb range.  Anya is 2-3yo with brown eyes and a dark nose, Atka is 10-12mos with blue eyes and a light colored nose.  We believe they are a mix of Siberian Husky and Chow; based on build, coat type, tongue color.

Both dogs are now crate trained.  We use Vari Kennel Ultras, they do not challenge their crates, or crate doors, and they readily go in.  Anya will climb chain link, or wire, therefore a privacy fence would be ideal.  Or, monitored potty breaks with lots of leash walks.  On the two occasions that Anya did climb out of our fence, she ran around the house, and sat down on our front porch, while we caught up to her and let her back inside.  Yes, accidents happen, and dogs do get out...that is why ID tags and microchips are so important.  We are working on house manners.

For additional information or an adoption application please email us... kaleidoscopek9s@yahoo.com

animal.description:
Meet Wilkie!   Wilkie is an older, more distinguished senior gentleman. He gets along GREAT with all dogs and cats. He even made good friends with the foster's cat!  

Wilkie can be hard of hearing and his eyesight in one eye is limited. It doesn't seem to bother him one bit though, as he has become used to hand signals for things such as “time to go outside”.  He can get startled if he doesn't see you coming due to his limited vision and deafness, therefore a home with older children or adults only would be best. 

Wilkie likes to go for short walks around the block and roam the yard for all the good smells. Wilkie takes treats so gently and loves to get spoiled with some extra biscuits.  

This salt and pepper senior is very resilient and is looking to live out his glory days with a family to call his own. He is on daily arthritis medicine that is very inexpensive and he takes it very well in a pill pocket.  

Wilkie’s ideal home would have minimal stairs.  His current foster home has two steps to get in and out and he navigates them fine. Anything more than that though could be too much for him. Rugs or carpet in the house could be helpful for him as it helps him get traction when moving around. 

He's a simple guy who just wants a blanket to sleep on, treats and some lovins every now and then. Apply to adopt this sweet gentleman on our website at www.rescueapittie.org

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Maggie came to the shelter as an owner surrender. Her owner was not prepared to handle a young, strong, and energetic dog. Maggie also did not get along with her owner's daughter's female dog, which is not uncommon. Maggie is a nice girl who is playful, loving, and a lot of fun. Maggie has been fully vetted and her fee is $125.

Maggie is a somewhat petite gal, weighing only around 50 pounds.

Maggie has had some basic training. She is not yet two years old, so she does still have some puppy playfulness. She is a lovely gal who adores her people but she does need to be the only pet in the home. Exercise is the key to dog happiness and Maggie needs someone who is willing and able to give her what what she needs. Kids over 10 would be best.

Need a running buddy? I'm your girl!
I'm a sweet girl!I can be alittle shywith people Idon'tknow, but I warmup quickly. I have lots of energy and I'm a very smart girl. I also love to cuddle.I may be 3 years old, but I'm a puppy at heart! I'd do best in a home with no dogs, no cats and no children under 13 years old. I'd love to be your one and only.

General Socialization Notes:

 I am a little shy with new people, but I warm up quickly. I am treat motivated. I'm still learning basic cues and manners, but I'm doing very well. I walk well on leash.SometimesI can be a little reactive on leash, but I've been working on that and I'm improving.I'm also housebroken. I don't necessarily love my crate, but I will go in with a yummy treat or chew toy.

Does London like other pets?

 I'd do best in a home as an only dog. Also, no cats, please.

Does London like children?

A home without children or older children, 13 years and older would bebest.

Favorite Toys:

 I lovestuffed animals, especially if they crinkle or squeak. I also lovemedium to tough chew toys/treats, especiallybully sticks!

Ideal Forever Home:

 I would do best in a home with a veryactive family. I'd love a home with a huge backyard where I can run and play. I would need a family willing to work with me and bond through training. I'd love to be an only dog and a home without cats would be best.

Macho is masked up and ready to meet his forever family!  He is a 1 yr old lover boy, who loves his people and wants to find a forever family where he can be their spoiled child. 

Macho was born to Mercy (yellow lab) last year and was adopted by a family who spent a ton of time and energy training him.  Unfortunately, as he got older, he and the resident senior boxer did not see eye to eye and it wasn’t fair to the original dog. 

He is a total sweetheart, but has some fear based quirks that need clear direction and guidance, without the use of force.  He has been working with our behaviorist, and the new foster/adopter will get continued support and sessions with her. animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Frankie! here is her shelter video and Freedom Day:

https://youtu.be/89nreGCYMPM

Meet our resident senior, Frankie, who is roughly 12 y/o, female, 50 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped. She ended up at the shelter because her owner passed away and we could not let this sweet girl perish so we saved her. Frankie arrived in Vermont weighing 90 lbs. and is much healthier now having lost over 40 lbs with a healthy diet and balanced active lifestyle! Her ideal home would be one in which her humans are home often and there are no other dogs; she is a diva and prefers all of the attention (even though she lives with her furry foster sister dog)! Frankie loves to go for car rides and be outdoors with her family; with her current foster, she has enjoyed paddle boarding, camping, and walks! She is potty-trained and great with children. Frankie would enjoy a more rural, quiet setting with a yard. She gets scared of loud noises and traffic, but loves to lounge in the sun and roll in the grass! Frankie is incredibly easy to care for, so grateful for her 2nd chance, and ready to find her forever home!

If you are interested in adopting Frankie please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site) thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out her Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

This is Miss Percy who was dumped in the shelter we think because she was sick and had had many puppies born and taken. She was sad and withdrawn at the shelter. But once she left that place and felt safe, everything changed! The following is from a fellow rescuer who went to visit: I walked in and said, Hi princess! and her whole body started wiggling. She acted like she has known me for years! All she wanted to do was sit with me and give LOTS of kisses. Her eyes were bright and she had the most beautiful calm energy. We sat together for a while and then she was ready to go inside. She let me know by going to the door, standing at it and looking back at me. I let her in and she went straight to her kennel, grabbed a quick snack out of her food bowl, and then curled up on her blanket This lady is so delightful, happy, and clearly has embraced the indoor only dog lifestyle. Its just amazing to me how grateful these dogs are for a warm bed. She doesnt know it yet, but Percy has a brand new life ahead of her. Shes destined to be someones forever princess 
This girl is only 7 years old and has plenty of life and love to give! Please consider giving her a chance!

animal.description:
Twiggy, (58 lbs. and growing. 12/24/20) is about 1 yr. old, named for her long slender model like legs. She might also be named because of her fascination with twiggs and bushes; whos to say? Little is known of the life she led prior to joining our care but its certain Twiggy missed classes about crossing streets and dumpster diving. Luckily, she is a master at giving kisses and loving on her people. Twiggy enjoys affection, hugs, kisses, snuggles, and being very close to her people. She hasnt mastered the concept of personal space so expect lots of snuggles in bed.

Twiggy can understandably be a little shy meeting new people but she is friendly to people she has come to know and trust. Shes great with other dogs but is definitely curious about those small fluffy things her humans call rabbits and squirrels.

Twiggy is learning to enjoy car rides especially because this means frequent trips to Belmar Nature Park where she has already made several dog and human friends. She needs a slight boost to get her butt in the car, she is able to jump down. On nature walks she loves watching the wild life, sniffing, enjoying the park, and of course living up to her name and finding twiggy branches. She likes to remove the small twiggy branches and gallop around, happy as a clam!

Twiggy originally ended up in an overcrowded shelter due to an injury. Thankfully, 2BABR saw past that and rescued her from the euthanize list anyway! Twiggy had FHO surgery in mid-December and is recovering very well. She is able to easily climb 32 stairs about 4-5 times a day, walks 2-3 miles over several walks. She likes to walk at a moderate to a fast pace. She is working on small hills to strengthen her right leg. She is able to walk with a slip lead sometimes at a comfortable loose lead but is often excited to go see friends or go back to her new foster home. She is cooperative with the word wait, release when we cross the street. She has not been asked to sit on command due to her recovery but is learning stand to leash up. 

It will be important for Twiggy to continue strengthening her right hip. Twiggy does go on city walks around Lakewood with her foster sister, Lucy, and a few other friends in the pack. While busses and cars seem ok, garbage trucks and loud metallic dumpster noises concern her. 

Twiggy will need a secure yard with a 6ft fence. Despite her injury if she gets spooked she can easily climb fences under 6ft. Shell also need continued training as she likely has had no formal training in her past. She has been attending weekly group classes and is doing very well! She is learning to transfer these skills to the busy outside world. She is respectful of older dogs and gets along very well with her bossy foster sister Lucy who reprimands her for being rambunctious in the house. She loves to chew on her toys stuffed animals and definitely has an energetic, puppy play-style.

Twiggy still has the puppy wonderment and the joy for life as any young dog should. She is playful but is an awkward 1 year-old dog. It is unknown how she would interact with young children as she is a bit gangly and uncoordinated, she could possibly knock them down. It is unknown how she would do with cats as she has not been exposed at my home. 

Twiggy is looking for her forever home who will love her long legs and appreciate her wonderful demeanor! She has a zest for life and know shell spoil any person/family with so much love and joy!

 

*Homeownership Required!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

Birdie is a little shy to new people, but get down to her level and she quickly loses that shyness. She's pure sweetie with a little sprinkling of spastic lab to top if off. This sweet lab does what all labs do, goes from 0-60 in 2 seconds flat. Birdie performs wonderfully with dogs of all sizes and isn't afraid to let the big dogs know that she's here to stay. We highly recommend she go into a home with another dog to help build her confidence with her humans.

 

Birdie is 98% potty trained (just 1 accident) and sleeps through the night in her kennel. She is kennel trained and will go to it if asked. While she hasn't been around children, we do recommend older children as younger children may frighten her. She loves playing with toys, chasing or being chased by other dogs, and enjoying a good cuddle at your feet. She'll love anything involving activity. If Birdie is the lab you're looking for please send in an application to meet her today.

animal.description:
Posted 11/14/2020

Alice and Flo came to us because their human had to go to a nursing home.  It was her wish they remain together and from observations from their Foster Mom, they are truly inseparable.  

Alice and Flo are approximately 1 year old Terrier mixes.  THEY ARE NOT HYPOALLERGENIC AND DO SHED. THEY HAVE NEVER LIVED WITH CHILDREN.  Alice and Flo are very energetic when they play in the yard, but in the house they just want to snuggle.  They truly crave attention and want nothing more than to be loved on and sit in your lap!  The girls are working on leash manners (they apparently were never walked on a leash) and basic commands (it's a good thing any approved applicant will take them to class).  They are house trained and crate trained.  Alice and Flo have been spayed, microchipped, fully vaccinated, tested and treated for intestinal parasites, tested negative for heartworm and lyme disease and started on monthly heartworm/flea preventatives.  If you want to add a little (because these girls only weigh about 8 lbs each) joy into your life, consider adopting Alice and Flo!  THEY REQUIRE A FENCED YARD AND SUPERVISION WHILE IN THE YARD.  

Adoption application, home visit and adoption fee required. If you would like to apply for adoption, please complete the online application at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under ADOPT tab. Please also read our Core Values prior to applying. Contact generalinfo@furryfriendsnetwork.com for questions or if issues are encountered with the adoption application or general adoption process.

Foster Homes are desperately needed in order to help more animals like this one. Please consider opening your heart and home to a homeless animal. To find out more about becoming a Foster Parent, see our website at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under VOLUNTEER tab.

animal.description:
Bender is a 3 year old Redbone Coonhound mix. Bender has a gorgeous red coat that shines! He is friendly to every person he meets and is a gentle giant weighing in at 70lbs.  But don't let his size intimidate you because Bender couldn't be more affectionate. Bender does great in the house and would prefer to be in a home with his family vs outdoors (unless his family is outside with him). Bender is kennel trained and he won't potty in his kennel.  He is house trained and does amazing with not having accidents inside as long as you take him out regularly. Bender likes other dogs but would do better in a home without other dogs,  or with another confident well trained dog that does not feel the need to be dominant.  Bender does good with female dogs and is okay with cats (especially kittens).  He does not like the dog park or dog day care type setting and would prefer to just be with his people . Bender is very passionate about the person he chooses as "his person" and would love to be by their side and follow them around 24/7. Even off leash outside Bender didn't try to run away from his prior foster family in TX. Anytime you give him the okay, Bender loves to snuggle up on the couch with you and spend quality time together. 

Bender came to us all the way from TX where there are more dogs in need.  His owner dropped him off at the shelter & he was put on a list to be euthanized which we could not let happen.  He has been with his foster home in TX that has shown him all of the ropes for a month now before making his journey up here to MN. 
 
----------------
Bold Animal Advocates is a holistic animal rescue who utilizes natural alternatives to traditional dog preventatives, medications, and vaccination when available & also feeds an optimal raw food diet. While not required to continue, preference will go to those willing to continue care holistically.

We value training and our dogs being well behaved members of our community so continued training for all of our dogs for the remainder of their lives is required.

We have recommendations on our website for companies that we love and trust if you would like suggestions.
boldanimaladvocates.com

We are required to charge sales tax on this adoption fee of 7.125% and accept cash, check, or Paypal at the time of adoption. Thank you!

Atari is a 2 year old hound mix who weighs 45 lbs. She is house/crate trained. She walks well on leash. Atari is heartworm positive, being treated. She is 2 months out of surgery to fix her hip dysplasia. In spite of pain she has endured prior to rescue, she is the most loving, happy dog. She dances when she is eating & constantly wags her tail. Atari gets along with most dogs but prefers calmer ones. She absolutely loves all people including children and is very gentle with everyone.  We have learned she would love a dog buddy in the home with not many stairs, along with a fenced yard.  We need new foster, as we are trying to figure out why she is gagging too often...has had $1,000 worth of tests to show nothing.  May have anxiety as she has had 2 long-term fosters & we are not sure what has happened for her.

animal.description:
ADOPT ME ONLINE: https://ophrescue.org/dogs/9014

 Hello. My name is Fionnuala (Fa Nu La)....... 
 I am a special little girl who came from a not so special place...
 I am thought to be 2 or 3 years old and weigh about 15 lbs. 
 Thanks to my foster mom and OPH for being such wonderfull people I am here and able to tell you a little about myself....
 I can be shy and nervous around new people and it can take me awhile to get comfortable with them but with the help of my wonderful foster mom she is showing me that all people are not like where I came from. 
 I don't mean to be rude. I am just scared and nervous. So don't be upset if the first time I meet you, I bark and back away this is still some of many things my foster mom is helping me to overcome..
 I had a rough start in life and need people to have a little extra patience with me.
Due to this I think I would do best in a calm house with kids over 12 who can understand what i have been through and give me some space to get use to my surroundings...
 I like most dogs, especially if they are close to my size. However, I tend to be a little possessive of my food and treats so it is best if you feed me in a separate area away from other dogs.
 I love to run around and play in my foster's fenced back yard and I can run really fast. Deer and squirrels and other animals really get my attention. Sometimes I think they would be fun to play with and other times I want to protect my yard from them...
So due to that, my foster mom thinks its best that I have a fenced in yard where I cant get out of in case that feeling comes to me to want to chase them...
I have to be in a secure harness and/or martingale collar with a leash because if I get loose, I will run and can be hard to catch....
I'm gonna need a patient adopter and one who is willing to help me with my training and help me trust again....
I am a very sweet girl and once I get to know you well I am a great snuggler. I am a special girl waiting for my special forever home... 
 I am crate trained and house broken is that a perk or what 
I am looking for a home to finally call my own.I will miss my foster mom but I will always remember without her I wouldn't be here to find my forever home..
So if that all sounds good to you apply for me and help me become the loving dog I know I can be with just a little patience and time.
To adopt this dog, or any OPH dog, fill out the simple online application at https://ophrescue.org 
Operation Paws for Homes, Inc. (OPH) rescues dogs of all breeds and ages from high-kill shelters in NC, VA, MD, and SC, reducing the numbers being euthanized. With limited resources, the shelters are forced to put down 50-90% of the animals that come in the front door. OPH provides pet adoption services to families located in VA, DC, MD, PA and neighboring states. OPH is a 501(c)(3) organization and is 100% donor funded. OPH does not operate a shelter or have a physical location. We rely on foster families who open their homes to give love and attention to each dog before finding a forever home.

animal.description:
Remember the class clown? That's Ace! 

This silly boy is a happy, big old dufas of a pup with a LOT of energy and is full of mischief. He will need an active home with someone to keep an eye on him. He would love to have a nice big yard to play in. He loves to go on hikes and long walks, and afterwards, get affection and play, play, play!

Ace can entertain himself for long periods of time with his toys and balls. He'd love to have you throw his ball, but if youre busy, he's perfectly capable of throwing it for himself!! If you're around and won't throw it for him, he'll throw it where he can't get to it and expect YOU to be the retriever!! He's very clever!

Ace needs to learn some manners but he is a bright boy and will learn quickly. He is fully vaccinated, neutered, microchipped and ready to go to his forever home today!!!

Ace is a staff favorite and we will hate to see him go, but he needs to get out of the shelter and into a family of his own. To find out more about Ace, meet him and see if this crazy pup is a good fit for you, text or call Julie Tuesday through Saturday between 9:00 and 5:00 at 435-773-5209.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Alaska! I was surrendered by my owner to Big Dog Ranch Rescue, along with my sister Reeci, after our owner passed away. We are bonded and it would be best for both of us if we could be adopted together. I am a good boy but very vocal and sometimes you might mistake those sounds as me being angry, but I promise I'm not. I like to play with other dogs, but I can be selective with who I choose to engage with. As a Husky, I most likely have a high prey drive and would probably prefer not to be in a home with cats or other small animals. I would ABSOLUTELY LOVE if I could find an experienced Husky owner who is aware of our high energy levels, large size, and high-maintenance grooming needs (I need to be brushed daily!). I would love a great big yard for me to run around in and I think I'd be happiest living a rather quiet lifestyle with my new family. I can be a bit protective of my territory so it's best to go slow with me and let me warm up to you. I am most protective of my food and will become quiet vocal during mealtimes which may sound mean, but again, I am really a true sweetheart! I do require additional training, again I am VERY vocal, but I do appear to be potty trained and love to go for long leashed walks.

animal.description:
Dax
Lab/Bulldog Mix
Male
5 years old
74 lbs.
 
Go big or go home, that’s my motto! I’m Dax, and I’m all in when it comes to my love for life and I am a pro at playing, cuddling, and making you laugh!  I like to run, romp, and chase things in the backyard. Then I’ll power down for a good snuggle session on the couch. I’ll do almost anything for a treat or a Kong filled with peanut butter, especially show you one of my favorite tricks — sit, stay, and shake. Do you love hugs? Great! I give the best, biggest hugs!

I love humans so much but I do need to be the only animal in my future forever home and need to be in an adult-only home. I get worked up when I see other dogs on leash (and I’m a strong boy!) so a home with a big backyard is a must (no apartments for me, please!) And I just need a human who can set me up for success by walking me in quieter areas and is willing to invest time and energy in helping me with my leash manners. I’ve been learning SO much in my foster home and I’ve made amazing progress on leash! And I’m excited to continue to learn in a forever home.I’m crate trained but also responsible when given free rein of the house. I’m just looking for a forever home where I can relax and be with my people!

Are you ready for a big, goofy, playful companion who will love you always?? Email my friends at PawsCo at adopt@pawscoadoptions.org or visit this information page: pawsco.org/adopt/adoption-process to fill out an application.

animal.description:
Please read through thoroughly and carefully before applying for Gina. She is a great dog but needs a special home. Gina is a gentle soul with a sweet disposition. Her ideal day would consist of sunning herself in a beautiful backyard during the morning and cuddling with her human on the couch in the evenings while she catches up on Grey's Anatomy. She does not always get along with other dogs. She has nice leash manners, and house manners and is always up for anything whether it be a stroll around the block or napping at your feet. Gina came to us with an ectopic ureter which caused her to leak urine; because of this she had constant infections and chronic pain. Since coming to us she has had surgery to correct the problem but sadly it was not successful. Gina will likely need to wear a diaper while in the house. She tolerates them well. Someone who works from home or is retired will likely be the best fit. This sweet girl would love a home of her own where she can relax and continue to enjoy life! She is crate trained and bounds in anytime she's asked. She has shown to be on the quiet side in her foster home and doesn't do much barking. She is incredibly responsive and comes quickly whenever her named is called, in fact, she's rarely far enough away from her foster mom's side where she needs to be called. She knows a couple basic commands such as sitting when asked and waiting for her food bowl to be put down on the ground or to come through the door. She seems to ride well in the car and jumps in for every adventure. She also sits nicely for her ears to be brushed and groomed. She really is wonderful and would make a fantastic devoted companion to anyone looking for a delightful and cheery shadow.

Gina is not recommended for homes with children. She has offered to bite two in a previous home. She is reactive to fast and loud movements.
animal.name: Gina

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****
Applicants MUST BE a minimum of 25 yrs old to ADOPT.


My name is Roden, I was rescued from a shelter in south Texas when I was a 2 month old puppy then adopted by a young lady who had me for a year and returned me to my foster mom because she no longer had the time for me. I then moved to NY where I was adopted to a family with a 1 year old dog but unfortunately we did not see eye to eye all the time. You see I need time to decompress and understand where I am and my new sister did not understand this so I would get mad at her when I was done playing but she wasn't. I'm a young dog who likes to play but I like to settle down as well, I need a dog who understands dog language and can respect my boundaries when I'm ready to sleep or be lazy. For this I think I would be best with a family with another quieter/calmer dog. With people I am a super sweet loving boy who wants all the kisses & cuddles! I may be a little timid for the initial meeting but after a bit I will show you my easy going demeanor. I also love running around outside to play! I am a young guy at only 1.5 years old so I still like to jump and hop around & younger children may not be the best fit without some coaching. I'm very good at listening and it doesn't take much to correct me or recall me. I am really good in the car & love to go with you on adventures. "
I am wanting a home with a fenced in yard and a canine buddy already in the home for me to play with. 


Name: Rodan

Age: 6/9/2019 

Current Weight: 50#

Rescued from: Texas, found as a stray originally.

Health: up to date on required vaccines

Adoption fee: $375

Rodan was rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. He will be arriving at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY on 11/18/2020 ready for adoption!

To apply to adopt Rodan, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Meet Wendy the chi-beagle! Wendy has been with us since right before the Covid quarantine began. She and 6 others were discovered living near an old tree stump down south.  They had clearly been dumped there and were trying to survive. Wendy was heavily pregnant and all 7 had clearly never been socialized around people. Wendy had no interest in having help from humans with her puppy delivery. She was very wary of people...as time went on, her puppies grew older and were adopted at the beginning of August. Wendy then went to a loving foster family who could spend time with her and get her to come out of her shell...
here is what her foster has to say:
What a journey!! Wendy has been with us for 4 months and has come such a long way! She’s still working on her fear of boys but is a perfect lady! She just wants to be loved and to make friends.  Her favorite things are rubbing herself on the lawn and drinking rain puddle water.  Loves long walks in the park and a quiet place to observe her surroundings (loves her crate for this).  She’s easy to love but will need a very patient human to help guide her to trust and a fur buddy (also loves cats). Wendy is between 3-4 years old. 
If you are interested in giving Wendy a loving and patient home, apply on our website!!! *no children under high school age...and another dog/cat in the home would be great!

animal.description:
Hunter is 3-4 years old, 40 lbs
Hi, my name is Hunter! I am very sweet, handsome, loving, and looking for my forever family! I was found emaciated, but in my foster home I have gained weight and foster mom says I'm very healthy now. I love lots of exercise, tough chew toys, snuggles, and treats. Boy, do I love treats! I was a little wary of humans at first but since being in my foster home, I've learned to trust them and be more confident in myself. I snuggle my foster parents while they watch movies and foster mom says I give the very best hugs and kisses! She also says I may need some training once I’m with my forever family to work more on my confidence and house manners, but I am very, very smart and learn really quickly! So far in my foster home I’ve learned how to ‘sit’ and wait patiently when there’s something I really want, like those treats I mentioned earlier! I am also house broken and crate trained. I occasionally nip to get attention or try to play with my foster parents, so foster mom recommends I be in a home with older teens or adults and no small children. Since I have lots of energy, I’d be really happy to have a fenced in yard and/or someone who will run or hike with me! Older dogs haven’t liked how energetic I am, so if my forever family has other dogs, foster mom recommends they be close to my age and energy level! I will fit right in with a patient and active family. I have a lot of love to give & can't wait to meet my forever family!

animal.description:
Name: Frank
Primary Breed: German Shepherd
Gender: Male
Entry Date: 10/12/20
Birth Date:  *02/2019
Adoption Fee:  $150.00

Full Description:  My name is Frank and I'm so ready to find my forever family. I'm extremely loyal and desire to be with my people all the time. I'd really love a home where I will not be left alone often. As is common for my breed, I am very intelligent and enjoy working my mind just as much as I enjoy playing or going on walks. I am a large guy and very strong, and I do need some work on my leash manners. I'd appreciate a home with German Shepherd experience, but it is not a requirement. I really value my one-on-one time with humans and would probably do best as the only pet in your home. Please call the Mason City Stray Animal Shelter at 641-424-3617 for more information.

Adoption fee covers the following veterinarian services: spay/neuter surgery, age appropriate vaccinations, flea and dewormer treatment, feline leukemia/FIV test in cats, heartworm test for dogs.

 

Animals listed with the Mason City Stray Animal Shelter will be held for 7 days from the “Entry Date” to give the opportunity for an owner to reclaim them.  If not reclaimed, the animal will be made available for adoption to the public.

animal.description:
Lou is looking for someone very special to give him a chance, whether it be a foster home, or a forever home--he is hopeful to have a place to call his own.

We won't put it lightly...Lou is a very scared boy who needs someone with experience with nervous/fearful/under socialized dogs. He will follow his human/foster around everywhere, but still has hesitations with petting and touch from people. He is extremely friendly with other dogs, and should be placed in a home with at least one other dog as he has always been surrounded by the comfort of other friends and really enjoys some company. He needs a fenced in yard where he can potty and play, and a home that will be able to dedicate the time to getting him more socialized with humans and how to be a confident dog.

We would like to see Lou go to the forever home that he deserves, and we will be waiving his adoption fee. DO NOT APPLY if you do not have experience with nervous or fearful dogs!!!! We need someone serious to step up for Lou so he can have a successful life as a house dog.
Click below to get started:

https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/TGD/Dog
or
https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/TGD/Dog

animal.description:
Ethan is a low-key senior that is just looking for a loving family to call his own. He appears to be a Shepherd/Chow mix, with the characteristic black tongue. With his coat and coloring, we think he looks a bit like a tiny lion! He has a very pretty coat, but will shed in some seasons. He doesn't exactly love being brushed, but will tolerate it within limits.

Ethan spends most of his time napping on his foster's bedroom floor, never wanting (and even disliking) being on the furniture. He is generally very low energy, spending majority of his time sleeping and finding a toy to toss around occasionally. Tennis balls are his favorite. He has some mobility issued though so he doesn't play too much. Ethan can also be a bit grumpy at times, and should be handled accordingly. He fusses and whines over too much cuddling, but loves getting head scratches. Those are his favorite and he comes up to beg for more! He will allow his foster to pick him up, but not fail to complain. Ethan will be best suited with a somewhat experienced dog owners and with no young kids in the family.

He likes going for walks, though we limit them given his arthritis. He also has a tear in one leg, though the vet didn't feel a surgery at his age would be advisable. He gets around just fine, just slowly. He may benefit from some pain meds if needed, but we have not been doing that since he is a master at pill detection, no matter how good you are at hiding them. He has done fine without them. He is housetrained and very good about coming up to you when he needs to go out. He may ask to be let out once in the middle of the night, depending on the schedule. Guess all seniors can have similar issues :) He lives with 4 other dogs and does well with them. But he may not like high-energy dogs being too rambunctious around him.

Ethan is neutered, up to date on his shots and was treated for heartworms, but now clear. He does have some eye issues and currently gets eye drops. His next follow up is in 3 months, but it is possible he may need meds permanently. He has decent vision (it improved as the meds started working), but he can't hear very well. Not a problem really since he doesn't generally get into anything.

If you are looking for a chill companion dog, Ethan may be a great addition! 2/2/21 3:35 PM

animal.description:
Hazel is a 9 mos old 20 lb Greyhound mix. In foster in olympia, WA  No apartments/condos she can be noisy. MAYBE perhaps a specific condo if noise doesn't travel 
 
Do you know Hei Hei, the rooster, from Moana?  Then you will be familiar with the personality of our beautiful Hazel!  Hazel is a 9 month old mostly Italian Greyhound.  
 
 
Making sense of her surroundings is probably never going to be fast or easy for Hazel.  Once she does, she will surprise you with her determination to accomplish some goal she has fixated on such as chewing Christmas tree lights, playing with the cat (which she does by sitting on her hind legs and windmilling her front paws around in the direction of the unimpressed cats), pulling the bed out of the Bully girl’s crate and sleeping on it even if it is upside down.  
 
She will run super fast with the Italian Greyhound hops every 2 or 3 feet and she can jump very high!  When something is in her path outside or inside she will whine until you show her how to get around it or remove the obstacle.  When she gets tired or confused which happens often she will put her nose against a wall usually in a corner and be silent.  If you don’t know her usual spots you almost need a GPS tracker to find her in your house. Hazel is not now and maybe never will be entirely house trained.  
 
She hasn’t been able to walk on a leash yet but now that she is staying awake longer we are working on that.  If she is agitated by too much commotion she will try to climb onto the head of the nearest human.  Hazel is unable to be left alone at this point in her life but that may change as she gets older and grows comfortable in a forever home.  
 
For all of these reasons the ideal home for Hazel will be one in which someone is able to be with her at all times, there is another smallish dog for her to follow outside and snuggle with inside, probably no children or at least not very young children, no rentals due to her loud voice and lack of house training, and the understanding that this is a very special needs dog so you decide not so much to get a pet but to take on a new fur kid but she is welll honestly a project.  

The rescue had medical in Tx. Since being here in Olympia, WA we have had a complete exam with the vet, fecal, full blood panel, x rays and toxicology exam. NOTHING is wrong with her physically that we or the vets could find. (yes her vet bill is close to $1000 just since being in the NW), not counting all her other medical, transport, etc. 
   

This is a posting for L & S Dog Diggity Rescue. You can fill out and application below. Yes you must COPY and PASTE this application link. 

https://shaynesrescue.com/adoption-application-ls-dog-diggity/

All adopted pups and dogs are transported to WA/OR families when fully vetted, spayed/neutered and microchipped.For information on how to adopt me, please contact my foster parents at info@dogdiggityrescue.com. L&S Dog Diggity Rescue is headquartered in San Antonio, Texas, where there are over 350,000 homeless pets. We save homeless and abandoned dogs and find them loving forever homes in other areas, where pet homelessness is not epidemic. All of our pets are located here, in San Antonio, and we partner with  rescues to provide transportation for our pets to their new homes. Our adoption fee includes vet care (vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchipping, etc), as well as transportation and health certificate. Please contact us to ask about our adoption process and our adoption fees. You can contact us directly at info@dogdiggityrescue.com, or fill out an application at  https://shaynesrescue.com/adoption-application-ls-dog-diggity/ 

Important: If you are interested in this pup/dog, please fill out the application (link listed above). The rescue will contact you once the application is received. Although we strive to answer everyone, due to the high volume of inquiries we receive, we cannot guarantee a response to all emails. Filling out the application is the ONLY way and ensures a response from the rescue. In addition, while you are emailing us, if others apply, you lose out adopting the dog you chose. We have hundreds and hundreds of puppies/dogs available so there really is no need to apply anywhere else. However, if you are applying or have applied anywhere else, we do need to know that.

SHANYE'S FOSTERS is a group of foster parents in the Olympia/Tumwater area. We foster dogs for rescues and assist them in adopting/rehoming of their pups/dogs by listing on this site. Many dogs posted here are available to pre adopt NOW directly from the rescue. The only ones in foster in the NW specifically state that. We have very few fosters so most need to be pre adopted. All adoption fees go towards rescuing more dogs in need. No one receives a salary. Shayne's Fosters is not responsible for any experience you have with any dog you might see posted on this site. They are the property of the sponsoring rescue who will supply all medical supporting records which is given with each dog when adopted.

Our adoption fees cover all medical costs to make sure the pups are appropriately vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and spayed/ neutered. It also covers the cost of transportation from Texas and the necessary health certificate documentation. The fees also include a negative heart-worm test for any dogs over 6 months. Some dogs/pups have additional medical, including but not limited to FHO, ACL, hernias, dental, and a myriad of other vetting. If the adoption fees seem high (which never cover the true cost of rescue), we recommend fostering for a good rescue. Fostering ensures you incur no vet bills and no boarding fees. We are always in need of good fosters. We are all volunteers who donate our time and resources to help save as many dogs/pups as we possibly can.

Thank you for choosing to adopt a rescue pup/dog. Worldwide over 1/2 or 1 billion puppies/dogs are PTS yearly. thousands and thousand daily (yes entire litters, pregnant/nursing moms are PTS daily just in U.S. shelters. Yes even entire litters of puppies yes DAILY in many US shelters! We firmly believe there is NO breed other than rescue for all species. Thank you for being part of the village it takes to save these precious lives.

animal.description: Meet Maya! This bi-lingual beauty is as smart as she is gorgeous. Maya was very loved by her previous family, but they had to leave the country and were not able to bring her. Upon her arrival at the shelter in November, Maya was pretty shy. Over a couple months, her personality blossomed and she bonded closely with kennel staff. Unfortunately, day after day she continued to be passed over for adoption. In hopes to learn more about her personality and match quicker with her future family, Maya went into foster care where she is quickly making herself at home! Maya is an expressive lady with a silly demeanor once she gets to know her people. When getting home after a long day, she will prance around and stare at the door to go outside or on a walk. Although happy to do her own thing, when she does want to show her lovey dovey side, she will nuzzle in the crook of your neck and has uncanny accuracy when it comes to licking you right on the mouth (kinda gross, but have to appreciate the sentiment!). Maya is quite chunky at this moment (almost 100lbs) and is working on improving the COVID bod. She loves walks and enjoys forcefully bossing around the other household pup. At around 6yrs old, Maya is pretty settled down, despite Husky breed stereotypes, and would be ideal for a laid-back bestie looking for a cat in a dog's body. Maya is simply looking for someone as special as she is. Think that may be you?

animal.description:
Xander is a healthy, male American Staffordshire Terrier who is 2 years old. He is fully house and crate trained, likes people, and does well with several commands, like sit, lay down, wait, come, quiet, paw and look at me.  Xander loves to be outside during the day whenever possible, and his evenings are mostly spent cuddling on the couch until bedtime. 
Although he is 76 pounds, he considers himself a lap dog. He is very food motivated and will come running if he hears you say ‘banana’, his favorite treat. He loves to go ‘bye-bye’ in the car and will make it to the door before you do when he thinks it’s time to go somewhere. 
Although he has lived with a confident older female dog without issue, he can be dog selective so he will do best as an “only child” which he loves because he enjoys being center of attention;) He has not been around small children, but has never shown any aggression toward guests, family members, or service providers (pool guy, plumber, pest control, vet) 
He is very tolerant of things like nail clipping, baths, and kisses on the face from mom. He is still working on perfecting his leash training skills! 
Xander is a very smart and handsome boy who is good natured, affectionate and a true people dog. 
He is looking for a family who has experience with his breed and can provide the structure and leadership he will thrive off of.??
**adopter must have secure, wooden fenced yard- no iron, no chain link, no apartments**

***Dallas area/metroplex adoptions only.***
The first step in our adoption process is to fill out an adoption application http://elmanimalrescue.org/adoption-application/.  This is how you meet our dogs and does not obligate you or ELMAR to adopt the dog; we are looking for the best match.
We reserve the right to deny adoption to any applicant.
All dogs and puppies are adopted with up to date vaccinations, spay/ neuter, microchip, dewormed, and thoroughly examined by our veterinarians. 
Puppies under 6 months - $250
Dogs over 6 months - $225

animal.description: This girl is the sweetest! She is an absolute love bug and her favorite thing to do is snuggle. If you are looking for a calm, mild mannered senior dog, this is the dog for you. She gets along with other dogs and cats just fine. She recently had a few teeth pulled but don't let that fool you, she is just fine with dry dog food. She has an adorable tongue now that sticks out to the side of her mouth from the teeth extractions. It definitely adds to her cuteness! She is heartworm negative, as well as her kidneys and liver in good condition. She is house trained, walks great on the leash and no bad manners like chewing stuff up. She loves to lounge in her dog bed, but most of all she just loves to follow me around. Please consider adopting Mazzie, she would be a great fit as the only animal in the house, or as an additional family member with other animals.

animal.description:
Nolan is a handsome large dog, primarily medium brown with black on his back and tail, and splashes of white on his muzzle, chest, and paws.
 Nolan is a terrific guy, looking to be in a loving household as the only pet in an adult family. He tends to be more naturally trusting of women, but can warm up to men once he knows them and their good intentions.
A smart fellow who is quick to learn, Nolan is happy to chill and relax with you in the house, and then head out with you on a brisk walk. Nolan has good leash manners and does well when meeting other dogs while out on his walks. He appreciates a good roll on the grass and would love a fenced-in yard.
Nolan is a gentleman inside, and is both house- and crate-trained. He enjoys his stuffed toys to chew on and wrestle with. He can quickly identify his own toys and leave your belongings alone. Did we mention that hes very smart?
So thats the package! If you are looking for a loyal, loving, intelligent companion, why not ask to meet Nolan? He is looking for the same!
 Nolan came into a local shelter as a stray.
 Read more about Nolan on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-20-178/.

animal.description:
Sadie Grove is black and white with short fur.
 Sadie Grove is a sweet and affectionate pooch who warmed right up to us! She has the biggest smile and loves to greet you with wiggles and wags. Check out Sadie's video and you will likely fall in love like we have!
Sadie is crate- and house-trained; and she knows several commands including Sit, Lie down, Stay, Go crate, and Away. She loves belly rubs and will ask for them by flopping over onto her back. She will also put her paw up to ask for pets. But she understands if it's not time for pets and will give you space. Sadie enjoys playing fetch and brings the ball back (when she wants to) 
She needs an owner who will stick to a training routine and who has a fenced-in yard. During walks, she gets very excited when she sees animals and sometimes people. Sadie's main exercise is in the backyard and she should only get walked early in the morning or late at night. Sadie is currently receiving professional training to work on her 'stranger danger' and leash reactivity, and her foster parents are seeing improvement every week. 
Sadie is looking forward to a dedicated and loving furever home!
 Sadie Grove was found in a field.
 Read more about Sadie Grove on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-20-200/.
